    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras enter today\u2019s slate leaning heavily on **Pete Crow-Armstrong** (77.34) and **Junior Caminero** (76.33) as our primary offensive engines. **Pete Crow-Armstrong** benefits from an elite matchup against Waldron; his score is significantly inflated by an optimal 14% platoon adjustment and an advantageous look at a high-xERA starter (7.83). Meanwhile, **Junior Caminero** locks into the two-hole against Williams, leveraging a strong combination of base projection and lineup leverage that makes him our most bankable high-ceiling asset. While **Kazuma Okamoto** (61.55) and **Chase Meidroth** (60.91) also cleared the 60-point \"Strong\" threshold, the decision to slot **Pete Crow-Armstrong** and **Junior Caminero** into key positions is driven by their ability to capitalize on specific pitcher inefficiencies, a vital strategy given our ongoing emphasis on elite speed and situational hitting.\n\nThe most difficult roster decision involved **Jerar Encarnacion**, who sat just shy of our 40-point \"Strong\" floor at 39.39. Despite a solid park factor, his production was dragged down by an unfavorable matchup against S\u00e1nchez and a projected eighth-spot start that limited his efficiency, leading the optimizer to favor the more consistent floor provided by **Luke Raley** (58.36). We are also monitoring significant external risks: both **Trea Turner** (53.93) and **Kyle Schwarber** (50.54) are facing Webb\u2014a tough assignment\u2014with a 40% rain risk hanging over their contest that could compromise their plate appearance volume. Unfortunately, we are also dealing with a zero-floor day for **Yordan Alvarez** due to a postponement, and **Christian Yelich** remains unavailable on the IL. We will continue to track the late-arriving lineup for **Gary Sanchez** and **Colt Keith** to ensure our projections hold steady as we chase the scarcest category: stolen bases.",
